INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-11-lesson-02','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Founder and Employee Vesting and Linear Vesting','cmf-module-2-11','text','## Your outcome

Explain the key ideas in Founder and Employee Vesting and Linear Vesting, distinguish evidence from assumption, and apply them to a practical digital-asset decision.

### Founder and Employee Vesting

Tokens allocated to team members may become transferable gradually.

### Investor Unlocks

Private-sale or venture-investor allocations may be released according to a schedule.

### Community Rewards

Tokens may be distributed for:

Participation

Governance

Development

User growth

Referrals

### Liquidity Mining

Users may receive tokens for supplying liquidity to a protocol.

### Treasury Spending

A project treasury may release tokens to fund salaries, grants, partnerships and development.

### Airdrops

Tokens may be distributed to early users or selected wallet holders.

Every release increases available or potentially available supply.

### Initial Token Distribution

Initial token distribution shows how the asset was allocated when the project launched.

Common categories include:

Founders and team

Private investors

Public sale

Community

Ecosystem development

Foundation

Treasury

Network rewards

Strategic partners

Distribution provides insight into:

Ownership concentration

Insider incentives

Governance control

Future selling pressure

Whether public participants received fair access

The names attached to allocations should be examined carefully.

A project may describe a large allocation as “ecosystem development” while the allocation remains controlled by the founding team.

The effective controller matters more than the category label.

### Founder and Team Allocations

Founders and employees may receive tokens as compensation for creating and developing the project.

This can align their interests with long-term success.

However, the allocation should be evaluated according to:

Percentage of total supply

Acquisition cost

Vesting period

Voting rights

Ability to stake locked tokens

Conditions for accelerated release

Transparency of wallet addresses

A team allocation is more concerning when it is:

Very large

Immediately transferable

Poorly disclosed

Controlled by one person

Combined with significant treasury authority

Acquired at almost no cost

Long-term vesting may improve alignment, but it does not guarantee responsible behaviour.

### Private Investors

Projects may raise capital from private investors before offering tokens publicly.

Private investors may include:

Venture-capital firms

Crypto investment funds

Strategic partners

Wealthy individuals

Early supporters

Their capital may help fund development.

However, they may receive:

Lower token prices

Preferential allocations

Governance influence

Shorter vesting periods

Additional rights

Consider an example:

Private investors purchase at 0.05

Public participants purchase at 1.00

The market price later falls to 0.40

Public buyers have lost sixty percent.

Private investors still hold an eight-times gain.

They may be willing to sell at prices public buyers consider extremely low.

### Public Distribution

Public distribution may occur through:

Public token sales

Exchange offerings

Mining

Airdrops

Open-market purchases

Community reward programmes

A broad public distribution may reduce insider concentration.

However, public availability does not automatically create fair distribution.

Automated systems, wealthy participants or professional investors may acquire a large portion of a supposedly open sale.

Evaluate the final ownership structure rather than relying only on the distribution method.

### Community and Ecosystem Allocations

Community allocations may fund:

User rewards

Developer grants

Marketing

Education

Governance participation

Liquidity incentives

These allocations can support adoption.

They can also create ongoing token inflation and selling pressure.

Ask:

Who controls the allocation?

What criteria govern distribution?

Are recipients creating measurable value?

How long will rewards continue?

What happens when incentives stop?

Are distributions transparent?

A community allocation controlled entirely by insiders may function more like a discretionary treasury.

### Treasury Allocations

A project treasury stores assets intended to support future operations.

Treasury tokens may fund:

Salaries

Development

Audits

Grants

Partnerships

Marketing

Liquidity

A treasury can strengthen the project’s financial resilience.

However, it creates risk when:

One person controls the wallets

Spending is not transparent

Most treasury value is held in the project’s own token

Large sales are required to fund operations

Governance participation is weak

Treasury tokens may not be circulating today, but they can become future market supply.

### Vesting

Vesting is the gradual release of restricted tokens over time.

It is intended to prevent founders, employees or investors from immediately selling their entire allocation.

A vesting schedule may contain:

A cliff

An initial unlock

Linear releases

Periodic releases

Performance conditions

Vesting can improve long-term alignment.

However, it primarily delays supply. It does not remove it.

### Cliff Period

A cliff is an initial period during which no tokens become transferable.

For example, a four-year vesting schedule might begin with a one-year cliff.

At the end of the first year, a portion may unlock at once.

The remaining tokens may then vest gradually.

Large cliff unlocks deserve careful attention because substantial supply can become available on one date.

### Linear Vesting

Under linear vesting, tokens are released gradually at a consistent rate.

For example, after an initial cliff, tokens may unlock every month for three years.

Linear vesting produces more predictable supply growth than a single large release.

However, it can create continuous selling pressure if recipients regularly sell unlocked tokens.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'','',2,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-11-lesson-03','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Milestone-Based Vesting and Staking Concentration','cmf-module-2-11','text','## Your outcome

Explain the key ideas in Milestone-Based Vesting and Staking Concentration, distinguish evidence from assumption, and apply them to a practical digital-asset decision.

### Milestone-Based Vesting

Some allocations vest only when particular objectives are reached.

Examples include:

Main network launch

User-growth targets

Revenue targets

Technical milestones

Regulatory approval

Milestone-based vesting may align rewards with project performance.

The milestones must be objective and independently verifiable.

A team should not be able to declare vague goals completed merely to release tokens.

### Token Unlocks

A token unlock occurs when previously restricted tokens become transferable.

Unlocks do not guarantee immediate selling.

Recipients may:

Continue holding

Stake the tokens

Delegate governance rights

Transfer them to custody

Sell part or all of the allocation

The market impact depends on several factors:

Unlock size

Current circulating supply

Trading volume

Market liquidity

Recipient cost basis

Market conditions

Recipient incentives

### Measuring Unlock Size

An unlock should be assessed relative to the existing market.

Suppose ten million tokens unlock.

That figure has little meaning without context.

If one billion tokens already circulate, the release represents one percent of circulating supply.

If only twenty million circulate, the same unlock increases available supply by fifty percent.

Relevant comparisons include:

Unlock as a percentage of circulating supply

Unlock as a percentage of daily trading volume

Unlock as a percentage of available market liquidity

### Supply Overhang

A supply overhang exists when large quantities of tokens are expected to become available for sale.

Market participants may reduce their willingness to buy because they anticipate future supply.

This can affect price before the actual unlock occurs.

Potential sources of supply overhang include:

Founder vesting

Investor unlocks

Treasury sales

Validator rewards

Court-ordered distributions

Token migrations

Ecosystem incentives

The market may already price in a known unlock.

However, the actual effect can still differ from expectations.

### Dilution

Dilution occurs when new tokens reduce an existing holder’s percentage ownership of the total supply.

Suppose you own one million tokens in a network with a total supply of one hundred million.

You control one percent of the supply.

If the network creates another one hundred million tokens and your holding remains unchanged, you now control only half a percent.

The number of tokens you own has not changed.

Your proportional ownership has declined.

Dilution can also affect:

Governance voting power

Staking share

Claim on protocol incentives

Scarcity

### Inflation and Demand

Supply inflation does not automatically cause a falling price.

Price depends on the relationship between supply and demand.

If demand grows faster than supply, the price may still rise.

If demand remains stable while supply increases, price may face downward pressure.

The relevant question is:

Is the network generating sufficient new demand to absorb the additional supply?

New supply may be justified when it funds:

Security

Development

Adoption

Liquidity

Useful participation

The economic value created should be compared with the value of tokens being issued.

### Ownership Concentration

Ownership concentration measures how much of the token supply is held by a small number of wallets or entities.

High concentration can affect:

Market stability

Governance

Liquidity

Token distribution

Public confidence

A large holder may be able to:

Move the market

Dominate governance votes

Influence liquidity

Coordinate with other insiders

However, wallet concentration data requires careful interpretation.

A large wallet may belong to:

An exchange representing many customers

A smart contract

A liquidity pool

A project treasury

A bridge

One individual investor

Wallet analysis should attempt to identify the entity or purpose behind each major address.

### Wallet Count Does Not Equal Holder Count

One person can control many wallet addresses.

One exchange address can represent millions of users.

Therefore:

Ten thousand wallets do not necessarily mean ten thousand independent holders

One large wallet does not necessarily mean one whale

Distribution analysis should combine blockchain data with information about:

Exchange custody

Contract addresses

known treasury wallets

Staking pools

Bridge reserves

Raw wallet counts can be misleading.

### Governance Concentration

Token distribution often affects governance power.

If voting power is based on token ownership, large holders may dominate decisions concerning:

Treasury spending

Protocol upgrades

Fees

Token issuance

Risk settings

Leadership

A token can be widely held while governance remains concentrated if:

Most holders do not vote

Tokens are delegated to a few representatives

Founders retain special powers

Exchanges vote with customer tokens

Early investors coordinate

Governance decentralisation should be evaluated through actual voting participation and influence.

### Staking Concentration

Proof-of-Stake networks use tokens to secure the blockchain.

If a small number of staking providers control a large percentage of staked tokens, they may gain significant influence over:

Block production

Transaction inclusion

Governance

Network upgrades

Liquid-staking services can further concentrate delegated assets.

A broad token distribution does not guarantee a broadly distributed validator set.

Ownership, staking and infrastructure concentration should be evaluated separately.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'','',3,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-11-lesson-04','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Free Float and Step 6: Examine Liquidity','cmf-module-2-11','text','## Your outcome

Explain the key ideas in Free Float and Step 6: Examine Liquidity, distinguish evidence from assumption, and apply them to a practical digital-asset decision.

### Free Float

Free float refers to the supply realistically available for active trading.

It may exclude tokens that are:

Locked

Staked long term

Held by founders

Controlled by treasuries

Permanently inactive

Deposited in strategic reserves

Low free float can cause rapid price increases because only a small amount is available for purchase.

It can also create severe declines when a large holder begins selling.

A token’s current market price may therefore be based on trading in only a small percentage of its total supply.

### Low Float and High Valuation

Consider a project with:

Token price: 2

Circulating supply: 20 million

Maximum supply: 1 billion

Current market capitalisation:

2 × 20 million = 40 million

Fully diluted valuation:

2 × 1 billion = 2 billion

Only two percent of the maximum supply circulates.

The token may appear to be a relatively small project based on market capitalisation.

Its fully diluted valuation already assumes a two-billion value.

For the price to remain at two units as all tokens enter circulation, demand must expand enough to support fifty times more supply.

### Token Burns and Supply Reduction

A token burn permanently removes tokens from usable supply.

Burns may occur through:

Transaction fees

Protocol revenue

Redemption

Scheduled destruction

Governance decisions

Burns can offset new issuance.

The relevant measure is net supply change.

If:

Fifty million tokens are issued

Ten million are burned

The total supply still grows by forty million.

A project should not be considered deflationary merely because it conducts burns.

### Buybacks

A project may use revenue or treasury funds to purchase tokens from the market.

The tokens may then be:

Burned

Held

Distributed

Used for compensation

Buybacks can support market demand.

Their quality depends on where the funds come from.

A buyback funded through genuine recurring revenue differs from one funded using capital raised from previous token buyers.

Buybacks should be transparent and economically sustainable.

### Supply Changes Through Governance

Some protocols allow token holders or administrators to modify:

Issuance

Maximum supply

Reward rates

Burn mechanisms

Vesting

Treasury distribution

This creates governance risk.

A fixed-supply claim is weaker when a small group can vote to change it.

Ask:

Who can propose the change?

Who can approve it?

What voting threshold applies?

Is there a delay before implementation?

Can users reject the upgrade?

Are emergency powers available?

Supply policy is only as predictable as the governance system controlling it.

### Bridged and Wrapped Supply

Tokens may move between blockchain networks through bridges or wrapping mechanisms.

A representation of the original asset may be issued on another network while the original asset is locked.

Supply data can become confusing because:

Original tokens remain locked

Wrapped tokens circulate elsewhere

Several bridges may issue versions

Data providers may count assets differently

A legitimate wrapping system should maintain appropriate backing.

If more wrapped tokens exist than assets held in reserve, the representation may be undercollateralised.

Always distinguish between:

Native tokens

Official bridged tokens

Third-party wrapped representations

### Token Migrations

A project may move from one token or blockchain to another.

During migration:

Old tokens may be exchanged for new tokens

The conversion ratio may differ

Deadlines may apply

Supply rules may change

Unsupported tokens may become worthless

Users should verify migration instructions through official sources.

Fraudsters may create fake migration websites designed to steal wallet credentials.

A migration can also alter the project’s distribution and governance structure.

### Supply Transparency

A credible project should provide clear information about:

Current supply

Maximum supply

Minting rules

Burned tokens

Major allocations

Vesting

Treasury wallets

Governance powers

Supply claims should be verifiable through:

Smart contract code

Blockchain explorers

Independent audits

Transparent dashboards

Public treasury addresses

Warning signs include:

Conflicting numbers

Undisclosed wallets

Unexplained supply increases

Privileged minting

Missing unlock schedules

Frequent changes to allocation categories

### A Token Supply Analysis Process



### Step 1: Record the Core Numbers

Identify:

Price

Circulating supply

Total supply

Maximum supply

Market capitalisation

Fully diluted valuation

### Step 2: Identify Future Supply

Examine:

Founder vesting

Investor unlocks

Validator emissions

Community rewards

Treasury releases

### Step 3: Analyse Distribution

Determine:

Insider ownership

Public ownership

Treasury control

Largest wallets

Governance concentration

### Step 4: Assess Demand

Ask whether genuine use can absorb future issuance.

### Step 5: Review Control

Identify who can mint, burn or change supply rules.

### Step 6: Examine Liquidity

Compare unlocks and large holdings with:

Trading volume

Order-book depth

Liquidity pools

Available exchanges

Supply should never be assessed independently from demand and liquidity.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'','',4,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-11-lesson-05','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','A Token Distribution Checklist and Key Takeaway','cmf-module-2-11','text','## Your outcome

Explain the key ideas in A Token Distribution Checklist and Key Takeaway, distinguish evidence from assumption, and apply them to a practical digital-asset decision.

### A Token Distribution Checklist

Before evaluating a token, ask:

What is the circulating supply?

What is the total supply?

Is there a maximum supply?

Who can change the supply rules?

What percentage currently circulates?

What is the fully diluted valuation?

Who received the initial supply?

What did founders and investors pay?

What vesting schedules apply?

When are the largest unlocks?

How large are unlocks relative to circulating supply and volume?

Who controls treasury tokens?

How concentrated is ownership?

Do exchange or contract wallets distort holder data?

How much supply is staked?

What creates new supply?

What removes supply?

Is supply currently inflationary or deflationary on a net basis?

Can network demand absorb future issuance?

Are the reported figures independently verifiable?

### Common Warning Signs

Potential warning signs include:

Very low circulating supply

Extremely high fully diluted valuation

Large insider allocations

Short vesting periods

Large imminent unlocks

Unexplained minting authority

Treasury control by one person

Supply figures that differ across sources

High inflation with weak adoption

Promotional focus on burns while ignoring issuance

Concentrated voting power

Little available market liquidity

Private investors with extremely low cost bases

Frequent changes to supply rules

Wrapped assets without transparent backing

One concern may be manageable.

Several interacting concerns can produce severe dilution, governance and liquidity risk.

### Common Misunderstandings

#### “A Fixed Maximum Supply Guarantees Price Appreciation”

Demand must continue, and governance must not be able to change the cap easily.

#### “Circulating Supply Includes Every Existing Token”

Locked, vested and reserved tokens may be excluded.

#### “A Token Unlock Means Everyone Will Sell”

Recipients may hold or stake, but the ability to sell creates potential supply pressure.

#### “High Fully Diluted Valuation Means the Token Will Reach That Value”

FDV applies the current marginal price to future supply. The price may decline as supply expands.

#### “A Broad Wallet Distribution Proves Broad Ownership”

One person may control several wallets, while one exchange wallet may represent many users.

#### “Staked Tokens Are Permanently Removed”

They may later be unstaked and sold.

#### “Token Burns Guarantee Deflation”

New issuance may exceed the burn.

#### “Founder Tokens Are Harmless Because They Are Locked”

They remain potential future supply and may already provide governance or staking power.

#### “A Low Token Price Means the Asset Is Cheap”

Supply and valuation determine scale, not the price of one unit.

### Module Summary

Token supply analysis examines how many tokens exist, how many may eventually exist and how they enter the market.

Important measurements include:

Circulating supply

Total supply

Maximum supply

Free float

Fully diluted supply

Token distribution shows who owns or will receive the asset.

Important groups include:

Founders

Employees

Private investors

Public participants

Communities

Treasuries

Validators

Vesting delays the release of tokens, while token unlocks make previously restricted supply transferable.

The impact of an unlock depends on its size, recipient incentives, market liquidity and existing demand.

Low circulating supply can support rapid price appreciation, but it may conceal significant future dilution.

Ownership concentration can affect market stability, staking and governance.

Burns and buybacks may reduce supply or create demand, but they must be compared with new issuance.

A complete supply assessment combines supply data with distribution, liquidity, demand and governance control.

### Key Takeaway

A token’s current price reflects trading in the supply available today.

Its long-term value will also be influenced by the supply arriving tomorrow.

Before evaluating any digital asset, understand how many tokens exist, how many remain locked, who will receive them and what incentives those holders have.

Supply creates the units. Distribution determines who holds the power.

The next module is 2.12: Inflation, Deflation and Token Burns.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,5,0,0,0,'','',5,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
